              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/30045612-papaphilly?shelf=micro-history">micro-history</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2573524416" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12524756821413803844"><a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/27404.Gideon_s_Trumpet_How_One_Man__a_Poor_Prisoner__Took_His_Case_to_the_Supreme_Court_And_Changed_the_Law_of_the_United_States' title='Gideon&apos;s Trumpet How One Man, a Poor Prisoner, Took His Case to the Supreme Court-And Changed the Law of the United States by Anthony Lewis' rel='nofollow noopener'>Gideon&apos;s Trumpet: How One Man, a Poor Prisoner, Took His Case to the Supreme Court-And Changed the Law of the United States</a> explore one of the significant court cases in American jurisprudence, Gideon v. Wainwright. <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/7045126.Anthony_Lewis' title='Anthony Lewis' rel='nofollow noopener'>Anthony Lewis</a> writes about the case that gave everyone the right to an attorney whether they can afford it or not. This is part History, Law, and the great American crime novel. He looks at not only the case, but the history of the right to a lawyer and surrounding times diametricall</span>
  <span id="freeText12524756821413803844" style="display:none"><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/27404.Gideon_s_Trumpet_How_One_Man__a_Poor_Prisoner__Took_His_Case_to_the_Supreme_Court_And_Changed_the_Law_of_the_United_States" title="Gideon's Trumpet How One Man, a Poor Prisoner, Took His Case to the Supreme Court-And Changed the Law of the United States by Anthony Lewis" rel="nofollow noopener">Gideon's Trumpet: How One Man, a Poor Prisoner, Took His Case to the Supreme Court-And Changed the Law of the United States</a> explore one of the significant court cases in American jurisprudence, Gideon v. Wainwright. <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/7045126.Anthony_Lewis" title="Anthony Lewis" rel="nofollow noopener">Anthony Lewis</a> writes about the case that gave everyone the right to an attorney whether they can afford it or not. This is part History, Law, and the great American crime novel. He looks at not only the case, but the history of the right to a lawyer and surrounding times diametrically opposed to giving that right. <br /><br /><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/27404.Gideon_s_Trumpet_How_One_Man__a_Poor_Prisoner__Took_His_Case_to_the_Supreme_Court_And_Changed_the_Law_of_the_United_States" title="Gideon's Trumpet How One Man, a Poor Prisoner, Took His Case to the Supreme Court-And Changed the Law of the United States by Anthony Lewis" rel="nofollow noopener">Gideon's Trumpet: How One Man, a Poor Prisoner, Took His Case to the Supreme Court-And Changed the Law of the United States</a> looks at Gideon, a lifelong petty criminal and pulls no punches. He is neither a good man nor a nice man. His life was a mess. Yet, the book never lets the reader forget that he has rights too and deftly ensures that the reader is left with the thought that this right protects the better segment of society along with the criminal class. <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/7045126.Anthony_Lewis" title="Anthony Lewis" rel="nofollow noopener">Anthony Lewis</a> pulls off this feat by showing how big the case became over the course of travels through the Federal court system, but always comes back to the local issue of Gideon in Florida. While the case affects everyone in the country, it also affects a petty criminal living a small life.<br /><br />This is a classic text and is a must read. </span>
  <a data-text-id="12524756821413803844" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


