  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2472090055" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2472090055" />
    <a title="Adam DeBord" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/77050458-adam-debord"><img alt="Adam DeBord" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2472090055?book_show_action=true">Apr 07, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Adam DeBord" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Adam DeBord" href="/user/show/77050458-adam-debord">Adam DeBord</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2472090055" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17666513000973910382">A relatively simple man of limited means sat alone in a prison in Florida. He is there as a result of a robbery of the Harbor Bay Poolroom in Panama City, which he claimed to be wrongfully convicted. This conviction was the result of his lack of legal representation in court. He couldn’t get one because at the time the court system operated under Betts v. Brady, which did not mandate court appointed counsel for any crime that wasn’t Capital. <br/><br/>He decided to take a Hail Mary throw and write to the </span>
  <span id="freeText17666513000973910382" style="display:none">A relatively simple man of limited means sat alone in a prison in Florida. He is there as a result of a robbery of the Harbor Bay Poolroom in Panama City, which he claimed to be wrongfully convicted. This conviction was the result of his lack of legal representation in court. He couldn’t get one because at the time the court system operated under Betts v. Brady, which did not mandate court appointed counsel for any crime that wasn’t Capital. <br /><br />He decided to take a Hail Mary throw and write to the last resort, the United States Supreme Court. His letter was full of misspellings and grammatical errors, a clear sign of his 8th grade education, but the improbable happened and they took his case.<br /><br />This set up the story of how Clarence Earl Gideon got his case heard in the Supreme Court. His name would go down in legend and be taught throughout the country from high school civics classes to criminal law and procedure classes in every law school in the country. This book tells his story.<br /><br />It does more than that because there is more to a Supreme Court decision than most people know, even people who follow the Supreme Court. This book explores the protocol and procedure the justices follow as they make decisions which case to hear, how they conduct oral arguments, how they vote, and how they draft their opinions.<br /><br />Along the way it also explores the legal question at the heart of this case: Can the Federal court system creat an obligation for states to provide legal counsel to indigent defendants? It explores this question through a historic review starting in the first attempt to answer the federal question in Baron v. Baltimore. It moves on to discuss the ratification of the 14th Amendment and the process of incorporation the Court adopted through its interpretation of the Due Process Clause.<br /><br />The right to an attorney was considered to be a fundamental right, necessary to ensure the right to a fair trial. With this in mind, the court reversed Betts and Gideon became the governing rule regarding the right to indigent defendants in getting legal representation.<br /><br />The book makes great use of this case providing an exception to Stare Decisis. From time to time, such as in this case or Brown v. The Board of Education, the court has an opportunity to revisit the rule it created in an earlier decision and correct its past mistakes. Each new Court builds on and critiques the Courts that came before it. The Court is still made of humans, and as such it is subject to human frailties, self-interests, and lack of foresight. Much like the union also created in the document that created the Court. It can only hope to become more perfect. It can never be perfect.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17666513000973910382" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


